name: Skill
Dice Reading
note:
<SG:2> <help>
<SG:>
<SG:
This game includes dice-based judgement such as in backgammon and combat. Generally, it is based on the concept that 'better outcomes are achieved with larger numbers on the dice',
making it possible to play without in-depth knowledge of the system.
However, to understand it more thoroughly, the usage of expressions such as "2d6" will be 
explained." d6" indicates ' number of 6-sided dice'. Therefore, \c[6]2d6 means 'rolling two 6-sided dice'\c[0].

\c[4]Example: When the results of rolling two dice are 3 and 4:\c[0]
 \i[754]\i[755]
 In this case, the result of rolling two 6-sided dice is "7", so the expression becomes "2d6(7)".

>

name: Attack Power (D Value)
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
The parameters of weapons are expressed with the number of dice + a fixed value.

\c[4][For example, in the case of D value "2d6 + 1"]\c[0]
 The total of the the two 6-sided dice and the fixed value (1) is the attack power.
 For instance, if the result of rolling two dice with this condition is 3 and 4 resulting in 7 
in total, the equation will be:
 \i[754]\i[755] + 1
 That is, 2d6(7) + 1 = 8.

Also, there are related parameters for weapons. 
In the case of a weapon with a "strength check", damage corresponding to the character's 
strength is added.
>

name: Criticals
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
If a weapon or skill has a \c[6]"C value"\c[0] set, 
 a critical occurs when the dice roll exceeds that value. 

\c[4][Example: If the dice roll is "2d6" and the C value is "12"]\c[0]
 If the sum of the two dice rolls equals 12, a critical occurs. 
 \i[757]\i[757] 
 A critical ignores the opponent's defense and doubles the sum of the dice rolls. 
 \c[6]Note that the C value judgement is only based on the sum of the dice rolls and does not 
reflect fixed values.\c[0]

 This judgement method also applies to enemy attacks.
>

name: Fumbles (Mistakes)
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
In actions where dice rolls are involved, if the roll result is the lowest possible value, 
the action is often judged as a failure. 
For example, in the case of 2d6, rolling the lowest possible value on both dice results in a fumble. 
\i[752]\i[752] 

Note that it is important to be careful as some bad states may increase the chances of fumbling.
>

name: Escape Rate
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
When attempting to escape from an enemy, a judgment occurs through dice rolling. 
The judgment is based on [1d6 + agility] ability value. 
Agility of the character who chose to escape will be referenced for this value. 
The success target value is determined by the enemy with the highest 'agility' among the surviving enemies in the enemy group. 

Escaping is only successful if the result of the ability value judgment exceeds the target value. 

\c[4][Example: Target value "8", character's agility is "4"]\c[0]
 In this case, a single die is rolled (1d6), and rolling 4 or higher is required. 
As the roll result (4 or higher) + agility (4) exceeds the target value, the escape is successful.
>

name: Bad States
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
The success rate of a bad state (BS) is determined when the user of the BS skill rolls the dice and the result is lower than the target's [luck * 2]. 

In other words, the higher the luck, the lower the chance of receiving a bad state. 

However, the success rate of a bad state caused by an additional effect of an attack depends on the success of that attack.
>

name: Level Up and Parameters
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
In this game, levels do not increase automatically. 
Each character manually levels up by \c[6]spending experience points\c[0]. 
When a character levels up, their HP and SP increase, and they gain parameter points. 

Parameter points can be allocated to each ability value such as strength and agility. 
Determine the character's aptitude and develop them as desired. 
Even if the distribution of ability values is incorrect, it is still possible to clear the game, but it is advantageous for exploration to develop a ranger-type character with high agility.
>

name: Skill Acquisition
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
Each character can acquire new skills by \c[6]spending experience points\c[0]. 
Basic skills can be learned at the Explorer's Association, and new skills can also be learned from skill books and other sources obtained from time to time. 

Since experience points are also used for leveling up, it is important to carefully consider which to prioritize when using them.
>

name: Combat Action Order
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
The speed of actions during battles is automatically determined internally by agility and dice rolls. 
The higher a character's agility, the higher their chances of initiating a pre-emptive attack. 
Some equipment items also come with modifiers to action speed.
>

name: Exploration Maps
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
This game features dungeons and other various locations to explore, which are typically in the form of a board game. 
The clear conditions often involve reaching the goal within a specified number of turns. 

Players can obtain various items or encounter battles during their journey on the board. 
There may even be some naughty events. 

There are useful items that can increase the remaining turns or allow the player to specify their movement steps. 
Therefore, it is important to make proper preparations before engaging in the journey. 

In addition, in the Explorer's Association located on Ancient King's Avenue, it is possible to recruit temporary comrades to join the exploration. 
Since \n[1] is weak, it is recommended to add allies to the party if possible.
>

name: Escape Maps
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
The escape map is basically the same as a normal exploration map, but it is extremely dangerous to venture alone. 

Furthermore, if the remaining turns become zero, players cannot return to the town and are forced to return to the starting point. 
Try your best to reach the exit somehow.
>

name: Combat and Bosses
note:
<SG:2> <help>
<SG:>
<SG:
During battles, there may be enemies with special text colors or icons. 
These indicate that they are bosses or strong enemies, and they receive modifiers to their parameters. 
Since there are many powerful enemies, be careful when facing them. 
Also note that defeating these enemies will reward players with increased experience points.

>

name: Types of Ailments
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
This is about the possible status ailments that can occur during battles or events: 
\i[2]Weak Poison - Receives [2] fixed damage per turn. 
\i[87]Strong Poison - Receives [5] fixed damage per turn. 
\i[326]Skill Seal - Skills are sealed for a certain number of turns. 
\i[4]Magic Seal - Magic is sealed for a certain number of turns. 
\i[3]Blindness - For a certain number of turns, the chance of fumbling (missing) in battle becomes the dice's lowest value + 1. 
\i[13]Bind - Unable to take action for a certain number of turns. 
\i[9]Stun - Unable to take action for that turn. 
\i[8]Sleep - Unable to take action for a certain number of turns; can be canceled by damage. 
\i[6]Confusion - Randomly attacks either an enemy or an ally for a certain number of turns. Chance of removal by damage. 
\i[764]Targeted - There is an increased chance of becoming an enemy's target for a certain number of turns
>

name: Contract Points
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
Through the Contract Mark's effect, \n[1] is now able to obtain \c[6]Contract Points\c[0].
In exchange, it's possible to extend the repayment date or exchange them for items.

There are no downsides to using the points.
Let's use them actively if obtained.
The Contract Points can be used at the Jimet Company in Nisshinko Street.

>

name: Sanctity
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
Sanctity is a parameter that represents \n[1]'s soul's purity.
It decreases bit by bit by obtaining a lewd constitution and other such things.
The Sanctity mainly serves as a requirement for obtaining "Additional Contracts" from the Contract Mark.

Note that the value of Sanctity itself does not affect the ending or anything else.
>

name: Lewdness LV and Lust
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
When experiencing a lewd event, \c[6]Lust EXP\c[0] increases.
This shows that \n[1] is becoming more lewd.

Once the Lust EXP reaches a certain value and the conditions are met, \c[6]Lewdness Lv\c[0] increases.
Lewdness Lv cannot be decreased, and serves as a condition for progressing to new events and stages.
It may also affect \n[1]'s speech and behavior.
Furthermore, it may affect the ending as well.
>

name: Skill Level
note:
<SG:2> <SG:><help>
<SG:
Here is an explanation on how to raise and what effects various skills have:

Church Rank... Rises through church duties and charity work. It affects the donation amount.
Service Rank... Rises through working at a bar. It affects the reward amount.
Sacred Arts Rank... Rises by healing others at a clinic. It's possible to learn new arts.
Lord Evaluation Rank... Rises through evil spirit subjugation. Additional rewards can be obtained for each rank.
Lewd Techniques Rank... Rises through serving others. It affects prostitution reward amount.
Dance Rank... Rises through dancing. It's possible to learn new techniques.
>

name: Food VS Magic Potions
note:
<SG:2> <help>
<SG:>
<SG:
Food and drink items have the effect of restoring the entire party's health.
However, \c[6]they cannot be used during battles.\c[0]
Also, there is a \c[6]limit on how many times they can be used per day.\c[0]

Magic potions, such as potions, are expensive, but have an immediate effect and \c[6]can be used even during battles.\c[0] Also, there are no limits on how many times they can be used.
Choose between the two depending on the situation.
>
